{{Italic title}} {{Infobox website | name = Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy | logo = | logo_size = | logo_alt = | logo_caption = <!-- or: | logocaption = --> | screenshot = | collapsible = <!-- set as "on", "y", etc, otherwise omit/leave blank --> | collapsetext = <!-- collapsible area's heading (default "Screenshot"); omit/leave blank if collapsible not set --> | background = <!-- for collapsetext heading; default grey (gainsboro) --> | screenshot_size = | screenshot_alt = | caption = | url = {{URL|http://www.iep.utm.edu}} | slogan = | areas = | offices = | traded to date = | commercial = | type = [[Online encyclopedia]] | registration = | language = | num_users = | content_license = <!-- or: | content_licence = --> | programming_language = | owner = | author = [[James Fieser]] | editor = [[James Fieser]] and [[Bradley Dowden]] | launch_date = {{Start date and age|df=no|1995}} | revenue = | alexa = <!-- {{IncreaseNegative}} {{steady}} {{DecreasePositive}} [http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/example.com ##] (US/Global MM/YYYY) --> | ip = | issn = 2161-0002 | oclc = <!-- OCLC number, useful where an ISSN has not been allocated (automatically linked to http://www.WorldCat.org) --> | current_status = | footnotes = }}
The '''''Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy''''' ('''''IEP''''') is a scholarly [[online encyclopedia]], dealing with [[philosophy]], [[Philosophy|philosophical]] topics, and [[philosophers]].<ref>Oxford University ARCH Project, http://arch.oucs.ox.ac.uk/detail/87371/index.html, accessed 11 September 2017.</ref> The IEP combines [[open access]] publication with [[peer reviewed]] publication of original papers. Contribution is generally by invitation, and contributors are recognized and leading international specialists within their field.<ref>Oxford University ARCH Project, http://arch.oucs.ox.ac.uk/detail/87371/index.html, accessed 11 September 2017. See also Kooy, B. 2015. 'Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy', in ''Reference Review,'' Vol.29, No. 4, p. 12.</ref>
==History== The ''IEP'' was founded by philosopher [[James Fieser]] in 1995, operating through a [[non-profit]] organization with the aim of providing accessible and scholarly information on philosophy.<ref Kooy, B. 2015. 'Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy', in ''Reference Review,'' Vol.29,No.4, p.12; see also name="iepabout">{{cite web | title = About the IEP | url = http://www.iep.utm.edu/home/about/ | work = Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy }}</ref> The current general editors are philosophers James Fieser and [[Bradley Dowden]], with the staff also including numerous area editors as well as volunteers.<ref>'Law in free internet encyclopedia of philosophy (SEP and IEP)', in ''University of Chicago Library News'', 22 January 2011, http://news.lib.uchicago.edu/blog/2011/01/22/law-in-free-internet-encyclopedias-of-philosophy-sep-iep/, accessed 11 September 2017; see also Kooy, B. 2015. 'Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy', in ''Reference Review,'' Vol.29,No.4, p.12.</ref> The entire website was redesigned in the summer of 2009, moving from static HTML pages to the open-source publishing platform [[WordPress]].<ref name="iepstaff">{{cite web | title = IEP Staff | url = http://www.iep.utm.edu/iep-staff/ | work = Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy }}</ref>
==Organization == The intended audience for the ''IEP'' is philosophy students and faculty who are not specialists within the field, and thus articles are written in an accessible style.<ref>Kooy, B. 2015. 'Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy', in ''Reference Review,'' Vol. 29, No. 4, p. 12.</ref> Articles consist of a brief survey or overview, followed by the body of the article, and an annotated bibliography.<ref>Kooy, B. 2015. 'Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy', in ''Reference Review,'' Vol.29, No.4, p. 12.</ref> Articles are searchable either by an alphabetical index or through a Google-power search mechanism.<ref>Kooy, B. 2015. 'Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy', in ''Reference Review,'' Vol.29, No.4, p. 12.</ref>
==Usage== [[Similarweb]] analytics suggest that the ''IEP'' website is accessed worldwide between two and three million times per month.<ref>Similarweb data on IEP, at www.similarweb.com, accessed 18 September 2017.</ref> Some 75% of this usage is through internet searches, 18% is through direct access, and 5% through referral, with the referring websites including other reference websites and university library guides.<ref>Similarweb data on IEP, at www.similarweb.com, accessed 18 September 2017.</ref>
==Recognition== The ''IEP'' is included by the [[American Library Association]] in its listing of Best Free Reference Sites;<ref>American Library Association (Reference and User Services Association) website, http://www.ala.org/rusa/sections/ets/pubs/bestfreewebsites2016, accessed 11 September 2017.</ref> listed as an online philosophy resource by the Federation of Australasian Philosophy in Schools Associations;<ref>Federation of Australasian Philosophy in Schools Associations, http://fapsa.org.au/resources/guides-to-philosophy/, accessed 12 September 2017</ref> listed by EpistemeLinks as one of the "outstanding resources" in philosophy on the internet;<ref>EpistemeLinks, http://epistemelinks.com/, accessed 12 September 2017</ref> and listed as a reliable resource in many university philosophy guides.<ref>See for instance, Cambridge University, http://libguides.cam.ac.uk/philosophy/eresources, accessed 12 September 2017</ref>
