'''Peter Kenneth Dews''' (born 22 April 1952) is a British [[philosopher]], in the fields of [[critical theory]] and [[continental philosophy]]. He made his name with the ''Logics of Disintegration'', on the limitations of [[post-structuralism]].<ref name="BeaumontHemingway2007">{{cite book|last1=Beaumont|first1=Matthew|last2=Hemingway|first2=Andrew|last3=Leslie|first3=Esther|title=As Radical as Reality Itself: Essays on Marxism and Art for the 21st Century|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1Rc9sVG7tr0C&pg=PA49|accessdate=27 March 2011|year=2007|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-3-03910-938-8|page=49}}</ref> He is Professor of Philosophy at the [[University of Essex]].
His first degree was in English, at [[Queens' College, Cambridge]]. He has a doctorate in philosophy from the [[University of Southampton]].
== Work == * ''Logics of Disintegration: Post-Structuralist Thought and the Claims of Critical Theory'' (1987) * ''The Limits of Disenchantment: Essays on Contemporary European Philosophy'' (1995) * ''Deconstructive Subjectivities'' (Ed.) (1994) * ''The Idea Of Evil'' (2008)
